    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait what do you mean by \"goblin guard\" though? that sounds kind of weird. is that like a specific legal term or something? i just want to make sure i understand the actual process.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the \"goblin guard\" is just a silly metaphor I slipped in, not a real legal term like \"title insurance\" or \"escrow agreement.\" You're right to ask for clarity; the actual process is quite straightforward, even if it feels a bit like navigating a maze of tiny goblins trying to steal your keys.\n\nHere is the real deal on how it works:\n\n1.  **The Deposit:** When you make an offer, the money you're putting down (the earnest money) goes into an escrow account. This isn't given to the seller immediately. It's held in a bank account controlled by a neutral third party—usually a title company or a lawyer.\n2.  **The Waiting Game:** Both you and the seller have to do their homework. You get your mortgage approved, the seller gets their home inspected, and everyone checks the title to make sure there are no hidden debts or liens.\n3.  **The Release:** Once everything is signed off and the \"goblin guard\" (the escrow officer) confirms all conditions are met, the money is released. Usually, the earnest money goes toward closing costs, and the rest goes to the seller.\n\nSo, the",
